    "narrative": "Today\u2019s lineup is anchored by **Geraldo Perdomo**, who earns the top spot with a 68.41 score. Batting leadoff against Martin, **Geraldo Perdomo** benefits from a high-leverage opportunity to accrue counting stats, further bolstered by an elite 17% SP Skill bump against a pitcher with a 4.68 xERA. While our middle-tier hitters like **Bryson Stott** (59.07) and **Matt Chapman** (57.18) provide strong utility, **Bryson Stott** is the beneficiary of a solid platoon advantage (+13%), while **Matt Chapman** leverages the slow delivery of Glasnow to increase his stolen base probability, a critical factor given our aggressive pursuit of the SB category.\n\nOur secondary core, including **Luis Arraez** (54.16), **Gleyber Torres** (51.41), and **Jung Hoo Lee** (51.45), remains viable despite facing tough competition. **Jung Hoo Lee** offers a particularly interesting profile; his 10% platoon edge helps mitigate the difficulty of facing Glasnow. Conversely, **Drew Gilbert** (43.24) and **Wenceel Perez** (45.20) represent our lowest projections, primarily hampered by their position at the bottom of their respective lineups, which significantly caps their run-producing potential. \n\nRegarding bench decisions, the absence of **Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00edrez**, **Cal Raleigh**, **Will Smith**, and **Lawrence Butler** due to scheduled off-days or rest creates a thinning of the ranks, leaving our utility depth tested. None of the available bench options posed a serious threat to the current configuration, as the focus remains on prioritizing volume for **Geraldo Perdomo** and the middle-infield stack. We must remain wary of the heavy exposure to Glasnow today; while the matchup factors for **Matt Chapman** and **Jung Hoo Lee** are encouraging, any deviation from expected lineup order for players like **Drew Gilbert** could necessitate a late-game pivot to ensure we protect our daily efficiency targets.",
